AGI - Mint Butterfield, 16 years old, the heiress and unique daughter of two Silicon Valley giants mysteriously disappeared Sunday from the mother's house, north of San Francisco, continues to be a mystery. The police are beating the whole area looking for a track but there are no signs. The research concentrated in the district of Tenderloin, land of criminal gangs, homeless and drug dealing, where the girl might have gone looking for a shelter or maybe to meet someone.
&nbsp;
In the past Mint had problems with drug abuse and had manifested suicidal intentions. His disappearance is mobilizing the world of online platforms, also because his is not the story of any minor: the father, Stewart Butterfield, is the founder of the online messaging platform Slack, ceded in 2021 to 28 billion dollars; the mother, Caterina Fake, in 2004 founded the Flickr platform, a multilingual website, including Italian, where users can share photos. The site was then sold to Yahoo.
&nbsp;
The two app creators, very popular in the Silicon Valley, are separated since 2007, the girl's birth year. According to investigators, Mint left a note at home, where he said he wanted to leave and that he would take him behind a suitcase. He wouldn't have a cell phone and the car, two elements that would make it even harder to track.
&nbsp;
The county sheriff admitted that there is fear that the girl may have taken her life, even if the suitcase hypothesis leaves some hope. But with the passing of days, the situation gets more worrying. Investigators have, however, excluded the possibility of kidnapping with the aim of asking for a ransom to parents. A friend of the girl told she had seen Mint north of San Francisco, but she wouldn't provide any more useful details.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the signage photo of the young heiress has become viral on American social and media: the girl is described as tall a little more than a meter and fifty, gracile, long red hair, rigged eyes and eyebrow piercing. On social media there are those who tifa for his escape, and those who ask her to return home, but on X there is also those who cruelly say not to try empathy for a "feited, drugged and billionaire girl".
&nbsp;
The last time she was seen at home on Sunday night, she wore a black shirt, flannel pants and boots. The police made available a number of phone numbers, and asked in the various chat apps to report any detail. Everything can be useful, the sheriff explained, to trace the teenager who seems to have vanished in nothing for almost a week.&nbsp;

