Warren Harris apologized. To do so it took forty-seven years, all spent in a Louisiana prison, which was once a slave plantation called Angola, along the Mississippi River. At 63, Harris gave a turn to his life, officially apologized for the triple murder in New Orleans when he was 16, he was made of heroin, and he stabbed three people he wanted to take away the money. For those three murders he was sentenced to life, but for him the prison doors will open up thanks to repentance and a rehabilitation program. In the state penitentiary of Louisiana, Harris spoke for the first time in a video conference, in connection with the members of the commission who had to decide his release. He recognized he was wrong.
&nbsp;
"I have few grandchildren - he said during the hearing - I have one for which I pray every day because nothing happens to him and does not end up in prison like me. Not just him. Some of his friends, you know." The murders were committed within eight weeks between February and April 1977. In New Orleans, people were afraid there was a serial killer targeting the gay people in the French neighborhood. The area, with its Bourbon Street jazz, was presided over by police on horseback, but in the meantime many locals emptied for fear that the serial killer would again live, to stretch his blood trail.
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Instead, the killer was a stunned minor from the heroine, abandoned by the family, one who wandered on the street like a randagio in search of money to buy the doses.&nbsp;&nbsp; Nearly fifty years later he found himself in front of a monitor, to apologize, to admit that he was wrong and ruined the lives of many people. He dried his eyes several times, behind his glasses. Harris is among the 121 prisoners sentenced to life when they were minors to whom, since 2017, a hearing has been granted to review the sentence or turn the sentence inflicted into probation.
&nbsp;
To benefit from this treatment you must have taken at least twenty-five years behind bars. According to Sentencing Project data, a nonprofit that studies penitentiary systems, the United States is the only nation in the world that condemns life, and without the possibility of leaving, minors considered guilty of serious crimes. But in recent years in many areas of the country it is beginning to study forms of rehabilitation, even to contain the excessive expenses that long detentions involve. Since 2012 twenty-eight states and the district of which the capital Washington has banned the sentence to life for those under eighteen years. Currently in the United States there are 488 prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment for crimes committed when they were underage. Almost 1100 have been released since 2016.
&nbsp;
Harris was a boy when the police arrested him in a motel room. The victims lived a few blocks away. Harris had met them on the bus or on the street. Their names were: Jack Savell, Alden Delano and Ernest Pommier.&nbsp;&nbsp;"I needed money to buy me the drug - he told during the hearing - I became a friend of those three in different periods. They asked me to join them and follow them home. Time to get into the apartments, robbed them and killed them. I'm sorry every day." For each of the three murders, the boy was sentenced to life. So, three winches.
&nbsp;
Jerrie LeDoux, who is part of the commission that had to change the sentence on probation, now says he has asked many times: "I would be afraid to live next to this person?" His answer was no. "Well, you told him during the hearing, I think you're ready to go back to the street." At one point the woman asked him: "I want you to tell us now why we should authorize you to leave the prison." "I - Harris responded - rehabilitated myself. God has allowed me to reevaluate my whole life and to put me back on the right path." In prison he played trusted roles, learned to garden, completed a course on how to manage addictions, became a member of a gospel choir called "Pure Heart Messengers".
&nbsp;
Already in 2008, interviewed in a documentary, Harris had confessed to director Benamin Harbert that music had brought him inner freedom. "Music for me - he had explained - is like reading a western story and enjoying that story. You feel that character, you feel like riding along a plain, getting into a saloon etc." The day he listened to a gospel on the radio, called "Jesus, I love your name", he cried for emotion.
&nbsp;
Once free, Harris will live with her sister, Brenda Palmer, 60 years old. "I got pregnant at 14 years - she told the woman during the hearing - and grandmother at 40 years. All this time he saw Warren grow up. We were all ideally in prison with him."
&nbsp;
"Warren - he added - was like a father and an uncle for my children and my grandchildren. Everyone needs the other. When I went to see him all these years in prison, I didn't do it for him, but because I needed it. For this I am here and I will always be, until God will bring us all to his side." Harris took off his glasses and cried.&nbsp;

